{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1446"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1446"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.13,0.02,0.78,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32283"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17906"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"478"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44579"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32283"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one day history of vague chest pain and some mild shortness of breath. The shortness of breath is particularly evident when lying down. His medical history includes stable angina, but no other significant medical conditions. Upon further history, it is discovered that the patient had a minor fall off a ladder two days ago landing on his side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination is largely unremarkable with the exception of some dullness to percussion at the base of the left lung. ECG and cardiac biomarkers are unremarkable. A CT chest is performed, looking for the possibility of a traumatic pneumothorax (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely cause for this man\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiomegaly","Left ventricular hypertrophy","Right ventricular hypertrophy","Pericardial effusion","Congenital left ventricular herniation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scan shows a large\u003Cstrong\u003E pericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E. This man\u0027s presentation is suggestive of pericardial effusion with both retrosternal chest pain and orthopnoea. Dullness to percussion is also indicative and is caused by compression of the lung parenchyma by the pericardial effusion. The absence of any significant medical history does not decrease the likelihood of pericardial effusion which can develop idiopathically or alongside a number of other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be the cause as the heart does not appear to be enlarged on the scan.  A more significant cardiovascular history or displaced apex beat on examination might have been the case if cardiomegaly was the problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eright ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E would both be likely to be detected on ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital left ventricular herniation\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cardiac malformation that is often asymptomatic until a complication occurs. The CT scan does not fit with this diagnosis and there is no other information within the stem to suggest it.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In pericardial effusion, the heart shadow increases in size and the aortic knob disappears compared to cardiomegaly where the aorta is still visible.","Pericardial effusion may occur spontaneously with symptoms of chest pain and dyspnoea."],"references":["Khoshpouri P, Hosseini M, Iranmanesh AM, Mansoori B, Bedayat A, McAdams HP, Chalian H.  Acquired Pericardial Pathologies: Imaging Features, Clinical Significance, and Management.  Appl Radiol.  2021;50(2):10-15."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17906"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1446"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19096"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19096"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1ebf5c42-abe4-43d5-a291-ee16fa7b883f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1ebf5c42-abe4-43d5-a291-ee16fa7b883f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":595}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17906"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-07T17:37:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-02-07T17:37:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1446"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32283"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t